# Map Interface Deep Dive: Entry Set, Compute Methods, and Advanced Patterns

## Map Contract and Methods
`Map<K,V>` is NOT a `Collection`. It maps each key to exactly one value. Keys are unique; values may repeat.

```java
Map<String, Integer> scores = new HashMap<>();

// Basic operations
scores.put("Alice", 95);
scores.put("Alice", 98);    // replaces: Alice → 98
scores.get("Alice");         // 98
scores.get("Bob");           // null — key not present
scores.getOrDefault("Bob", 0); // 0 — safe null avoidance
scores.containsKey("Alice"); // true — O(1) for HashMap
scores.containsValue(98);    // true — O(n) full scan (avoid in hot paths)
scores.remove("Alice");      // removes and returns 98
scores.remove("Alice", 98);  // removes only if current value is 98 — conditional remove

// Size
scores.isEmpty(); // true
scores.size();    // 0
```

## Views: keySet(), values(), entrySet()
```java
Map<String, Integer> map = Map.of("a",1,"b",2,"c",3);

// Keys
Set<String> keys = map.keySet(); // {a,b,c} — a live Set view
for (String key : map.keySet()) { ... }

// Values
Collection<Integer> vals = map.values(); // live Collection view
vals.stream().mapToInt(Integer::intValue).sum(); // sum of all values

// Entries — MOST USEFUL for iterating key+value together
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " → " + entry.getValue());
    entry.setValue(entry.getValue() * 2); // modify during iteration — safe via entrySet
}

// Java 8 forEach — cleanest
map.forEach((key, value) -> System.out.println(key + ": " + value));
```

## Compute Methods — Idiomatic Map Updates
```java
Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
List<String> words = List.of("apple","banana","apple","cherry","banana","apple");

// Option 1: getOrDefault (verbose but clear)
for (String w : words) freq.put(w, freq.getOrDefault(w, 0) + 1);

// Option 2: merge — most idiomatic for accumulation
for (String w : words) freq.merge(w, 1, Integer::sum);
// merge(key, value, remappingFn): puts value if absent; applies fn(existing, value) if present

// Option 3: compute — transform existing value (can set to null to remove)
freq.compute("apple", (k, v) -> v == null ? 1 : v + 1);

// Option 4: computeIfAbsent — lazy initialization
Map<String, List<String>> groups = new HashMap<>();
groups.computeIfAbsent("fruits", k -> new ArrayList<>()).add("apple");
groups.computeIfAbsent("fruits", k -> new ArrayList<>()).add("banana");
// groups: {fruits: [apple, banana]}
// The lambda only runs if key is absent

// Option 5: computeIfPresent — update only if key exists
scores.computeIfPresent("Alice", (k, v) -> v + 10); // adds 10 if Alice exists
```

## replaceAll() — Transform All Values
```java
Map<String, Integer> prices = new HashMap<>(Map.of("apple",100,"banana",150));
prices.replaceAll((key, value) -> value + (int)(value * 0.1)); // add 10% to all prices
// prices: {apple=110, banana=165}
```

## Map.Entry — Building Sorted/Grouped Results
```java
Map<String, Long> ordersByStatus = orders.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Order::getStatus, Collectors.counting()));

// Sort map by value (descending count)
ordersByStatus.entrySet().stream()
    .sorted(Map.Entry.<String,Long>comparingByValue().reversed())
    .forEach(e -> System.out.println(e.getKey() + ": " + e.getValue()));

// Convert to sorted list of entries
List<Map.Entry<String,Long>> sorted = new ArrayList<>(ordersByStatus.entrySet());
sorted.sort(Map.Entry.comparingByValue(Comparator.reverseOrder()));
```

## Map.of() and Map.copyOf() — Immutable Maps
```java
Map<String, Integer> config = Map.of("maxRetries", 3, "timeout", 30);
// No null keys or values, no add/put/remove, no duplicate keys, no order

Map<String, Integer> safeCopy = Map.copyOf(mutableMap); // defensive copy
```

## Connection to Spring Boot
```java
// Application properties as Map
@Value("#{${app.config}}")
private Map<String, String> appConfig;

// Request/response with Map (flexible but untyped — prefer DTOs for APIs)
@PostMapping("/metadata")
public ResponseEntity<Map<String, Object>> getMetadata(@RequestBody Map<String, Object> request) {
    Map<String, Object> response = new LinkedHashMap<>(); // preserve order in response
    response.put("status", "ok");
    response.put("timestamp", Instant.now());
    return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
}

// Caching with computeIfAbsent
private final Map<String, List<Category>> categoryCache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
public List<Category> getCategories(String locale) {
    return categoryCache.computeIfAbsent(locale, this::loadFromDatabase);
}
```

## Common Mistakes
1. **`containsValue()` in a hot path:** O(n) — use a reverse index (second Map with value→key) if frequent value lookups are needed.
2. **Modifying the keySet() or values() and expecting the map to update:** they are views — modifications propagate, but adding to keySet() throws UnsupportedOperationException.
3. **`get()` returning null ambiguity:** does null mean the key is absent, or the value is explicitly null? Use `containsKey()` to distinguish, or avoid null values.
4. **Not using computeIfAbsent for nested structures:** manual null-check-then-put is verbose and error-prone; computeIfAbsent is atomic and clean.

